Title: Linking forum posts - analyze-2-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Big telescope vs No. of small telescopes
Input.posts:
Would a group telescopes with shapes of lens separated by certain distances together work as big lens which could be impossible. \xA0 \xA0I mean say an example of 100 meter lens telescope which in practical sense not possible but using a number of 1 meter lens with different(i predict) so that their virtual focus is made on computer to form an image so that we get an approximation of 100 meter telescope.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
I think the Very Large Telescope (VLT) is an example of a similar idea. The four independent telescopes can be used jointly to obtain higher angular resolution images of small objects on the sky. Also, arrays of telescopes are especially useful, and more widespread, in radio astronomy...the Jansky Very Large Array (VLA) and the Very Long Baseline Array (VLBA) are examples just to name a few...

Hi there everybody I was on a quick glance of the additional Wiki material when I realised that the unit conversion tutorial builds on the Imperial System. I was notably upset by this fact. As a European citizen I would like to encourage the use of the International System of Units, most especially concerning technical fields. Cheers
Upvotes:
16
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Jonas, welcome to the course! You are correct in that practically all technical fields rely on the SI units (meters, seconds, kilograms, etc.).\xA0 Aside from the humorous example in the wiki, there are more examples here http://www.chem.tamu.edu/class/fyp/mathrev/mr-da.html using SI units.\xA0 Also, sometimes we may be using units specific to astronomy, like the parsec, to more easily describe the distant universe

The professor did not include polarization as a possible fourth attribute of imaging. Is polarization filtering used in astronomy in any part of the EM spectrum?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Polarization of light in fundamental in some subjects in astrophysics.\xA0 For example, polarization of the Cosmic Microwave Background\xA0 and in the interstellar medium are two active areas of research.\xA0 I didn't include polarization in the lecture because to detect it requires very sophisticated instruments that are not commonly used in most detectors.

Input.threadtitle: Minimum amount of energy any sub-atomic particle can have.
Input.posts:
Hello, in the 'Nature of Light' page, there is: 'The Energy of a photon (γ) is defined as, where ν is the frequency of the photon, or the number of peaks in the wave pass a given point per second, and h is Planck's Constant , which is roughly 7×10-34 Joule•Seconds , whereJoule•Seconds are the same units as angular momentum, and (among other things) sets a limit for the minimum amount of energy any sub-atomic particle can have.' I don't see how this definition sets a limit for the minimum amount of energy. Why can't the frequency v be arbitrarily small?
Upvotes:
1
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Good question!\xA0 Equation (2) implies that within a light wave with frequency $$ u$$, the minimum possible energy of that wave would be $$h u$$, meaning there would be one photon.\xA0 However in general, any bound state will have quantized energy levels, and thus it will have a minimum energy.\xA0 This energy level is almost always dependent somehow on Planck's constant.\xA0 For example, the energy levels of an electron bound in the hydrogen atom are given by $$ rac{m_e e^4}{8 h^2 \epsilon_0^2} rac{1}{n^2}$$, where $$m_e$$ is the mass of the electron, $$e$$ is the charge of the electron, $$\epsilon_0$$ is the permittivity of free space, and $$n$$ is a positive integer.
Instructor's post : Good question!\xA0 Equation (2) implies that within a light wave with frequency $$ u$$, the minimum possible energy of that wave would be $$h u$$, meaning there would be one photon.\xA0 However in general, any bound state will have quantized energy levels, and thus it will have a minimum energy.\xA0 This energy level is almost always dependent somehow on Planck's constant.\xA0 For example, the energy levels of an electron bound in the hydrogen atom are given by $$ rac{m_e e^4}{8 h^2 \epsilon_0^2} rac{1}{n^2}$$, where $$m_e$$ is the mass of the electron, $$e$$ is the charge of the electron, $$\epsilon_0$$ is the permittivity of free space, and $$n$$ is a positive integer.

Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
About how many Cepheid variable stars have been observed in the Milky Way? In Andromeda?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
I do not know the answers off the top of my head. So I searched the internet a little. The Milky Way has a little over 46,000 cepheid variables. I was however unable to find anything concrete for Andromeda. I will search some more and let you know if I find a reliable answer.
Instructor's post : I do not know the answers off the top of my head. So I searched the internet a little. The Milky Way has a little over 46,000 cepheid variables. I was however unable to find anything concrete for Andromeda. I will search some more and let you know if I find a reliable answer.

Input.threadtitle: STAFF/Professor DS9 Smorgosborg Part 2: Problem with rescaling Please Help
Input.posts:
I cannot select both images and rescale using Frame/Match/Frame/WCS. I select one image and then why I select the other image, the first image is unselected. How do you select both images? When I do Frame/Match/Frame/WCS nothing changes. I am deaf and rely on captions to listen to lectures on DS9. Perhaps I missed so,ethin? Shoul I hold down a key while selecting the second image? Thanks.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
You do not need both images selected to match them up. What happens is that the other frame(s) should match their coordinates up to the frame that is selected. What image are you trying to look at?
Instructor's post : You do not need both images selected to match them up. What happens is that the other frame(s) should match their coordinates up to the frame that is selected. What image are you trying to look at?
